	<text>
		<body>
			<div type="entry">
				<pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary78.jpg"/>
				<dateline><date when="1862-06-21">June 21. Saturday 1862</date>. </dateline>
				<p>It was a <name type="weather">warm</name>
					<name type="weather">pleasant</name> day. <persName
						key="Lt Col Joshua K Sigfried"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper172"
						>Lt Col Joshua K Sigfried</persName>
					<orgName type="military">48 P</orgName>. came here to make his <objectName
						type="readible">affidavit</objectName> for back pay a very pleasant
					gentlemanly man. There are many good things happen in camp that need the
					surroundings to fully appreciate. <persName key="Jacob Bachenheimer"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper173"
						>Bachenheimer</persName> is a little fellow in my company, they call him a
					Jew - he is a printer by trade, and corresponded for a <placeName type="city"
						key="Scranton, PA"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl106"
						>Scranton</placeName>
					<objectName type="readible">paper</objectName>. His bravery is rather doubtful
					as in our battles he always got tired and lagged. He is the butt of his mess
					&amp; they torment him about his <objectName type="readible"
						>correspondence</objectName> especially - and about sketching his various
					scenes - which is especially pointed because he was never present. Today, some
					of his men came into his <objectName type="equipment">tent</objectName> and
					said, “<persName key="Jacob Bachenheimer"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper173"
						>Bachenheimer</persName> made one mistake in his sketch of the review and
						<objectName type="equipment">sword</objectName> presentation. Bachy, as they
					call him, said nothing, but one of course asked What it was - Why he has
					sketched <persName key="Ambrose Burnside"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper008"
						>Gen Burnside</persName> with hair on his head. <persName
						key="Ambrose Burnside"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper008"
						>Gen Burnside</persName> is bald. We all have our hair cut very short, and
					some show very considerable baldness, as my own for instance, And the saying is,
					that one has his hair cut like <persName key="Ambrose Burnside"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper008"
						>Gen Burnside</persName>. <persName key="Arnold" type="private"> George
						Arnold </persName>leader of our Band is full of fun. His imitation of the
					Irish is rich. He wears his mustache, about the size of a <objectName
						type="nature">calfs</objectName> tail, and makes a very odd appearance. He
					said he wore whiskers in <placeName type="city" key="Norristown"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl107"
						>Norristown</placeName>. An old fellow then, who loved to get off a good
					theory on others but didn’t on himself met him one day, says he <persName
						key="Arnold" type="private">George</persName> - get shaved - why - oh you're
					a good looking man but you look ridiculous you ought to have a clean face like
					me - come I’ll pay for a shave - well come along says <persName key="Arnold"
						type="private ">George</persName> - And as they were going along <persName
						key="Arnold" type="private">George</persName> asked him why he disliked his
					whiskers - Why, says the old fellow, you look so much like as if you had
					swallowed a jackass, and left the <objectName type="nature">tail</objectName>
					stick out. Well, says <persName key="Arnold" type="private">George</persName>,
					do you know what your clean shaved face looks like, No, what? Why you look as if
					you had swallowed a <objectName type="nature">tail</objectName> and left the
					jackass stick out. The old man stopped - thought while - Well I’ll treat
						<persName key="Arnold" type="private">George</persName>.</p>
			</div>
		</body>
